: "Low"}, {"time_utc": "08:30", "currency": "USD", "title": "Empire State Manufacturing Index", "impact": "Low"}], "editorial": "EUR/USD is trading at 1.14296 as the European session draws toward its close, sitting in a compressed range that has characterised much of the past fortnight. The daily chart tells a story of a pair that sold off sharply from the 1.1619 area in mid-June, found a floor around 1.1324, and has since been grinding in a recovering but increasingly directionless consolidation. The desk bias is neutral, and the price action is doing little to argue otherwise.\n\nThe structure story is one of a failed recovery attempt that has stalled beneath meaningful overhead supply. From the 17 June sell-off candle \u2014 a session that dropped nearly 130 pips and closed well off the highs \u2014 EUR/USD spent the back half of June building a base in the 1.1324\u20131.1400 corridor. The recovery from that base was constructive initially, with the 2 July session printing a sharp bullish candle that reclaimed 1.1430. However, since then the pair has been unable to sustain any meaningful push through the 1.1463 structure resistance zone, a level that has now attracted two distinct rejection responses. Above that sits a prior reaction zone around 1.1443, which has registered three touches and is acting as a ceiling that the market keeps bumping against without conviction. The broader picture shows lower highs relative to the June peak, which keeps the medium-term structure from being described as cleanly bullish.\n\nOn the H1 timeframe, the intraday narrative is one of a quiet drift higher through the London morning after a notable spike late in yesterday's New York session. That spike \u2014 from around 1.1406 up to 1.1462 between the 21:00 and 23:00 UTC candles \u2014 was followed by an orderly pullback into the 1.1420\u20131.1430 area overnight, and the European morning has seen price settle in the 1.1419\u20131.1444 band. The hourly candles are narrow-bodied and overlapping, suggesting neither side is pressing with conviction ahead of the afternoon's US data.\n\nToday's calendar carries meaningful weight for USD pairs. US PPI and Core PPI at 08:30 UTC represent the first significant inflation print of the week, and any deviation from expectations \u2014 particularly a hotter-than-anticipated reading \u2014 could reinforce dollar strength and push EUR/USD back toward the 1.1380 area or lower. Fed Chairman Warsh's testimony at 10:00 UTC adds another layer of potential volatility; any hawkish framing around the rate path would likely amplify a dollar bid, while a more cautious tone could give the euro room to test the 1.1463 structure resistance once more.\n\nThe read shifts meaningfully in either direction depending on how price interacts with these zones post-data. A clean hourly close above 1.1463 would challenge the current neutral stance and open a conversation about the 1.1587 prior reaction zone. Conversely, a sustained move back through 1.1380 on volume would suggest the base built through late June is giving way, and the 1.1324 prior low would return to focus as the key structural reference to the downside.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}